學科別分類



中文摘要
十九世紀中葉，中國開港通商，而臺灣也在此一浪潮下與國際經濟體系接軌。臺灣南北通商口岸由於產業體系相異，以致在貿易活動上呈現不同的發展。過去研究在地域上重北輕南，忽略臺灣區域性差異；也缺乏觀察口岸商人複雜的互動關係，而逕以競爭觀點論述華洋商的勢力消長。故本文聚焦於安平口岸華洋商的互動關係，指出洋商為了打入本地自清初以來建立的商業體系，藉由買辦制度和本地掌握購銷網絡並具有相當資本的華商建立合作關係，洋商提供資金，而由買辦負起在口岸市場圈的經營和風險責任，以進行砂糖和樟腦輸出，及鴉片輸入貿易。但同時買辦也得以享有洋商勢力的保護及稅率優惠，因此買辦制度下的合作關係實基於互惠考量而成立。買辦利用多元策略與安平口岸市場圈上下游的糖商及鴉片零售商建立供銷管道，加以本身原即有多角化的投資經營，故得以累積相當貲財。1895年政權轉移後，洋商關註的樟腦和鴉片貿易受臺灣總督府實行專賣制度之影響而停滯，但買辦則因有穩固的商業網絡及經營多元商品而未受打擊，甚至投註於洋行的資金也超過洋商，更進一步利用華資成立「洋行」，企圖拓展國際貿易市場。即使新進的日商試圖進佔安平口岸市場，也不得不與華商配合，重回以買辦制度為中心的合作關係。這顯示安平口岸華商既有強固的勢力，無論面對洋商或日商都展現極強的耐受性。


英文摘要
According to the Treaty of Tianjin, Anping was opened as a treaty port in 1865 as part of the international economic system. At Anping Treaty Port, there was a complicated relationship between Chinese and foreign merchants. Foreign merchants utilized compradors, who had control over local business networks and owned substantial capital, as a way to enter the local business market that was established since the beginning of the Qing dynasty. In terms of their collaborative relationship in the export of sugar and camphor and the import of opium, foreign merchants provided financial capital while compradors managed the business and took on the responsibility of risks. Meanwhile , compradors also enjoyed the benefits and a preferential tax rate that was given to foreign merchants under the [unequal] treaties. Therefore we can conclude that cooperation through the comprador system was based on a principle of reciprocity. Through multiple strategies, compradors established supply and distribution networks with sugar and opium retailers at Anping Treaty Port. Moreover, with multi-investment management, compradors accumulated a certain amount of capital.In the beginning of Japanese rule in Taiwan (1895-1945), foreign merchants could not retain their hold on the camphor and opium trading business because of the Japanesemonopoly system. Nevertheless, compradors were not affected due to their stable business networks and their multi-product business management. Compradors invested even more capital in foreign companies than their foreign partners. They further used Chinese capital to establish ‘foreign firms’ and attempted to expand their international trading business. When Japanese merchants attempted to participate in the Anping sugar trade, they had to cooperate with Chinese merchants and thus adopted the comprador system. This demonstrates the economic strength of Chinese merchants at Anping Treaty Port as they showed great persistence in dealing with both Western and Japanese merchants.


